\begin_layout Standard
The program (in its current iteration) runs through a .bib file and extracts
 the title and authors.
 If no author is found, it prints the title of the entry and the message
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no author available
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 If the author cannot be assigned a gender by GenderComputer, it prints
 the author entry.
 Typically, these are cases of (1) initials (e.g.
 (2) organization (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The PLoS Medicine Editors
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) or (3) names that do not appear in the avaible databases, usually those
 of non-Anglo origin or with non-Latin characters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The script adds 1 to the appropriate array (man, woman, unisex, unassigned)
 until it is done running through the database, and then calculates the
 proportions of each category compared to the whole, generating the chart
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:Gender-distribution-div"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

